Comments: crack extending from top down the to inscribed name
Other Description: Thin slab with small hole near the top on the right side and another on the right edge
Full transcription as it appears on the: G.W. SMITH | Departed this life. | Aug. 1, '09
Other Associated artifacts, plantings, o: This marker faces west at the end of a rectangular plot bordered by a low curb on three sides, composed of three rectangular slabs of concrete or soft stone, once secured by concrete. At the west side, there is no curb visible, but two rectangular posts seem to mark the entrance to the plot, on either side of the thin marker. A little further to the west is the marble socket base for a larger marble headstone (also for GW Smith) that now rests against the northern post. Inside the plot at the west side near the headstones and raised post are the fragments of at least two vessels (one ceramic with blue floral pattern, one white porcelain with relief design) and three conch shells.

Occupation: Letter- carrier and vice president of branch 496, National Association of Letter-Carriers
Transcription of Printed Material: A Letter-Carrier Honored  Mr R. Bruce Evans, one of Richmond's most popular letter-carriers, and vice-president of branch 496, National Association of Letter-carriers, visited the recent unveiling in New York and was accorded a post of honor in the parade.  There were in line about 1400 letter-carriers in uniform, who were sub-divided and each division was under command of a station superintendent. Mr. Parsons, the National President desiring to honor Richmond had Mr Evans to assume the duties of station superintendent and coommand [sic] one of the division He was also presented with a handsome souvenir by Mr. Parsons. Infact, he was received and treated royally by the N w [sic] York carriers, and branch 496 appreciates the honor most highly.

Mr. Evans’ Sudden Death.   This community was shocked on Monday morning, 23rd inst., to learn of the death of Mail-carrier R. Bruce Evans, who while on his way to work fell on Venable St., and died before he could reach home.  The immediate cause of his death was hemorrhage of the lungs. He was popular with all classes, being a prominent mason and St. Luke. He was a member of the Baptist Church at Woodville of which Rev, Jacob Turner is a pastor. Mr. Evans was also a licentiate minister. He waa a devoted husband and father.  His funeral took place at the Fourth Baptist Church. Rev. Turner preached an impressive sermon. Eulogies were delivered by visiting pastors.  Funeral Director W. Isaac Jchnaon officiated.
Notes and Clarifications: Member of the Baptist Church at Woodville under Rev. Jacob Turner

Fraternal and Beneficial Organizations: A.F. Masons, Henrico Lodge No. 41; IOSL (Independent Order of St. Luke);
Transcription of Printed Material: A Good Man Gone. The funeral of Mr. R. Bruce Evans who departed this life suddenly on Monday morning lest while on his way his post of duty at the Richmond P. O., took place from the 4th Baptist Church on Wednesday evening the 25th inst. His pastor, the Rev. Jacob Turner of Mt. Tabor BaptisT Church officiating, adjusted by the pastor of the Fourth Baptist Church, the Rev. Evans Payne.  The deceased being a worthy young, licentiate of Mt Tabor Baptist Church in high esteem by the clergy of this city, and its vicinity as was evidenced by the presence of 21 pastors and aspirants, among whom were the following upon the rostrum: Revs. Jacob Turner, Evans Payne, J. H. Holmes, D. D., Wesley F. Graham, D. D. , J. H. Brice, P. S. Lewis, B D.. J. J, H. Binford, T. H. Briggs, P. C. Cobbs, J. Andrew Bowler, R. J. Bass, R. Beecher Taylor and D. Webster Davis, B. D. Short eulogies on the life and character of the deceased were delivered by several of the above named divines. Resolutions of Condolence were read by Revs. R. Beecher Taylor and J. Andrew Bowler, the latter on behalf of the Executive Board of the Virginia Baptist Sunday School Convention.  The choir of the Fourth Baptist Church, assisted by members of other choirs of the city and vicinity rendered music and the entire services were most impressive. Henrico Lodge, No. 41, Accepted and Free Masons, ol which he was a 32 degree member was in attendance; also Al Borsk Temple of the Mystic Shrine, on behalf of which most appropriate resolutions were read by Past Master Prof. Hugo Johnston. ' The Past Chiefs’ Council of the city of Richmond was well represented and furnished a handsome floral design, which was carried in a special carriage by Past W. Chiefs Maggie, L. Walker, Ella Onley, Emma Johnson, Mary Garrant.  Mt. Tabor Council, I. O of St. Luke, with which the deceased was connected for 20 years was out in large numbers, P. W. C., R. M. Monroe, presiding The PostMaster and the Superintendent of the Richmond Post Office, occupied seats upon the rostrum.  The floral designs which were many were furnished by station “A” of the Richmond Post Office, the National Carriers Association, the Main Office of the city, Union Prospect Council, I. O. of St. Luke of which he was a trustee, and by many dear friends whose names we could not get. The honorary pall-bearers were Messrs. E. A. Washington. W. M. T. Forrester, Eddie Cook and Rev. S. H. Dickerson. The active pall-bearers were representatives from the Virginiarious organizations with which the deceased was connected.
Notes and Clarifications: Religious Affiliation: Mt. Tabor Bapt. Church under R.V. Jacob Turner

Fraternal and Beneficial Organizations: Rose Croix, Thomas Stringer Chapter; A.F. Masons, Henrico Lodge No. 41; IOSL (Independent Order of St. Luke);

Fraternal and Beneficial Organizations: GUOOF (Grand United Order of Odd Fellows), Invincible Lodge, No. 2674; Knights of Pythias, Venus Lodge, No. I 46.
Transcription of Printed Material: The funeral of Ryland Lewis took place at the First Baptist Church last  Sunday at 1 o'clock. Rev. J. H. Fauntleroy read Psalm XXIII. Prayer was offered by Rev. Scott C. Burrell. Rev. W. T. Johnson delivered a most impressive sermon, "from the text, "God shall wipe away all tears from their eyes.” At the conclusion, Mrs. W. T. Johnson sang with transcendent sweetness of voice "In That City.” The letter from the distressed widow stated that death had come December 3 at 5:15 A. M. The deceased left a wife, son, sister, brother to mourn their loss.  He was a member of Invincible Lodge, No. 2674, G. U. O. of Odd Fellows, and also Venus Lodge, No. 46, Knights of Pythias. He had been a member of the First Baptist Church for more than twenty years.  Rev. Johnson and the congregation joined in singing "Sleep On, Beloved, Sleep and Take Thy Rest.” The floral designs were numerous and costly. The casket was cloth-covered, with heavy silver-mounted handles. Funeral director, A. D. Price, officiated. A touching letter of condolence was read from Mrs. Thomas M. Rutherford, in whose family he had labored so many years.

Fraternal and Beneficial Organizations: GUOOF (Grand United Order of Odd Fellows), Invincible Lodge, No. 2674; Knights of Pythias, Venus Lodge, No. I 46.
Other Documents to Consult for Research: Census (1880, 1900, 1910); city directories

Materials: marble; top two elements (pyramidal top plus round finial) appear to be made of rose granite; concrete base below ground level
Above ground height (in centimeters): main pedestal: 95; base and top elements: 28
Width (in centimeters): main pedestal: 26; base and top elements: 65
Thickness (in centimeters): main pedestal: 26; base and top elements: 65
Other Description: The rectangular pillar / pedestal is now standing upright next to a multi-tiered base but is clearly not in situ, as a 2014 photo in Find A Grave shows it lying on its side on the ground. The pedestal probably originally stood above the fourth (pryramidal) tier of the base, with the smaller elements that are now stacked on top of the base originally set on top of the pillar. Another 2014 photo on Find A Grave (by John Shuck) shows the base empty, without the smaller elements stacked on top.
Decoration: relief crosses in inset squares in horizontal bands set at top and bottom of pillar; elaborate multi-tiered base; top elements that probably once stood atop the pillar include small palmette and volute pediment and acroteria on each face and a round finial above a pyramidal top
Full transcription as it appears on the: IN MEMORY | OF OUR DEAR | MOTHER | SALLIE P. CLARKE | 1853-1918 | To live in the | hearts of those | I leave behind is | not to die. | Erected by her | Children ; (on the west face of the base, on the second tier in relief:) CLARKE
Other Associated artifacts, plantings, o: There is another tablet-style (rectangular slab) marker for Sallie (given by her husband) and a matching one for Ann M. Clarke, Sallie's mother-in-law, in the same plot. The plot is bordered by a low concrete curb with raised posts (with molded tops) flanking the entrance on the west side. The tiered base stands in the center of the plot directly across from the entrance, with the side with "CLARKE" in relief facing the entrance / west.
Marker_Transcription: Grave #1: (In Memory | Of Our Dear Mother | To live in the | hearts of those | I leave behind is | not to die | Erected by her | Children) Grave #2: (My Wife | Asleep)

Comments: Pedestal with Virginiaulted top, standing atop a two-tiered base. The left side of the monument commemorates Kate, while the front (facing the plot entrance) commemorates her husband William.
Decoration: The top is a pointed arch with three-lobed interior border encompassing a crown carved in relief, set in the middle of a wreath (laurel?). Below the inscription is a band of leaves and berries (also laurel?) carved in relief. The same decoration is repeated on the back side of the tomb stone (without the inscription). The front side has similar decoration (with a large M in relief in place of the crown) and an inscription for her husband William Mitchell. The upper tier of the base on the front contains the name MITCHELL in relief lettering, bordered at top and bottom by a horizontal band with a recessed three-lobed / triconch Virginiault in the middle
Full transcription as it appears on the: KATE M. HARRIS | Wife of | WM A. MITCHELL | Born | May 29. 1870 | Died | July 29, 1907 | Rest in Peace
Other Associated artifacts, plantings, o: in center of plot enclosed by concrete posts and metal rails.

Transcription of Printed Material: Mrs. Julia Covington Passes .Away. Entered into eternal rest Sunday, July 13. at the residence of her daughter-in-law, Mrs. Edna Murphy Morris. 2 110 Carrington Street, Mrs. Julia Covington, after an illness of several months. She had heen a faithful member of t li o Fifth Street Baptist Church for quite a number of years. She was a conscientious Christian, always ready to lend a helping hand. She bore her sickness with patience. She will be missed from the neighborhood being loved by all who knew her. Her funeral took place from the Mt. Olivet Baptist Church, Rer. Joseph Wheeler officiating. Her casket was a Spartan bronze metallic furnished by our popular young undertaker, Mr. Robert C. Scott. Interment in East End Cemetery.

Title of Article/Chapter/Essay: Mary White Dandridge Laid to Rest in East End Memorial Cemetery, Richmond, Virginia
Transcription of Printed Material: MARY WHITE DANDR1DGE LAID TO REST IN EAST END MEMORIAL CEMETERY, RICHMOND, Virginia Mary White Dandridge, daughter of the late Rev. G. and Mary A. White, who departed this life in New York City. Wednesday, June 9. 1926, was buried here Saturday at 2:30 P. M. The services in New York City were conducted by Rev. Dr. II. A. Booker and those in Richmond were conducted by Rev. Dr. S. C. Burrell, of the Y. M. C. A., assisted by Drs. W. T. Johnson, pastor of First Baptist Church; T. J. King, pastor of Fifth Street Baptist Church; A. D. Daly, pastor of Fifth Baptist Church; Dr. A. S. Thomas, Rev. G. Roane and others. Solo by Mrs. Ella P. Carter.  ihe services were impressive and consoling. The following members of the family accompanied the remains to Richmond: Rev. Dr. Thos. H. White, of Jersey City; Mr. Jos. White and Mrs. Martha E. Spencer and her daughter, Ruth D. Spencer, of New York City. The deceased leaves the following sisters and brothers, Mr. William White and Mrs. Elizabeth Jones, of Richmond. Virginia; Mr. Joseph White and Mrs. Martha E. Spencer, of New York City, and Dr. Thomas H. White, of Jersey City. The following gentlemen served as pallbearers: Honorary pallbearers —Messrs. W. H. Anderson, L. Storrs, Daniel Branch, John E. Scott, Rev. George Roane, Samuel Scott. Active pallbearers*—Messrs. James H. Brown, Joseph Poindexter, W. P. Logan, James Ullman. The following funeral directors, with great satisfaction to the family, directed the services: Messrs. W. C. Perry, of New York, and A. D. Price, Jr., of Richmond, Virginia

She ranks with the best in her profession.   She is prominent in fraternal organizations, namely: Courts of Calanthe, I. O. of St. Luke, I. O. of G. Samaritans, Household of Ruth, Tents, Sons and Daughters of Richmond, Shepherds of Bethlehem, and Ideal Benefit Society.  Your Patronage and influence will be greatly appreciated. Please remember that she is always at your service.   Reliable Service at Moderate Rates.  OFFICE: 3006 P Street, ‘Phone, Madison 2337.  RESIDENCE: 1015 St. James St. ‘Phone, Madison 6619.

Comments: Break on the left side and upper left corner of headstone. Break on right side and upper right corner of footstone appears to match, so it seems that this porcelain slab was broken in two pieces, and the larger was used for the headstone (did the break occur after the inscription had begun? That would explain why the footstone says only "ULYS."). The edges that are not broken are roughly squared and slightly beveled. The right side of the headstone is not exactly vertical. The back (uninscribed) surface of both the headstone and footstone are very smooth, while the front/inscribed surfaces have a fine-chiseled texture (except the bottom right corner of the headstone, which has a smooth concavity where a thin piece seems to have spalled off).
Other Description: Small thin slab headstone and smaller footstone that appear to be two joining fragments of the same stone

Transcription of Printed Material: Miss Mary Tancil Passes Away.  Mary L.. the young daughter of Dr. R. F. Tancil and Mary D. Tancil, died Wednesday morning, March 22, 1911. at 11 o'clock: aged 18 years. Funeral was held from Mt. Olivet Baptist Church, Friday, March 24, 1911, at 3 P. M’.

Other Description: (Marker replaced in 2017 after original marker stolen)

Transcription of Printed Material: DR. R. F. TANCIL GONE  The funeral services of Dr. R. F. Tancil, one of the best known physicians and public spirited citizens in this State, took place from the Mt. Olivet Baptist Church, Rev. J. Andrew Bowler, the pastor officiating. The services were inspiring and sympathetic and a large crowd thronged the church edifice and packed the streets surrounding the place of the impressive ceremonies. Funeral Director Robert C. Scott, the well-known transporter of the dead, had charge of the remains.  Rev. Bowler was at his best and coupled with the solemn anthems of the choir and other selected singers, the exercises will long be remembered on Church Hill. It would fill a book to give a detailed account of Dr. Tancil’s work among these people, where he had chosen to reside. He left a daughter, Mrs. Pearl Tancil Langston, who is now a resident of Philadelphia; a son, Richard F. Tancil, Jr. Mrs. Tancil had preceded her husband to the grave. The services took place at twelve o’clock last Sundoy. [sic]

Comments: top finial broken off, now lying next to base
Other Description: pedestal with Virginiaulted top that once supported a rounded finial or urn on an octagonal support (the finial is now lying next to the base, while the iron dowel is still in place on top of pedestal); two tiered rectangular base
Decoration: At the top of each face in the triangular/Virginiaulted space at the top is an incised circle enclosed by a circular band and with a horizontal band in low relief across it (in very low/worn relief behind the horizontal band is a motif that may be a torch); at the bottom of the pedestal on all faces, a horizontal band of some design (diamonds? egg-and-dart?) in very low/worn relief bordered by a thin flat band above and below
Full transcription as it appears on the: (on the north face:) GRACIE F. TAYLOR | DIED | NOV. 13. 1926 | HIRAM TAYLOR | DIED | AUG. 26, 1987; (on the west face:) JOHN B. TAYLOR | DIED | APRIL 12. 1929 ; (in low relief on top tier of base on the same side:)| TAYLOR
Other Associated artifacts, plantings, o: The lettering of the inscription for Hiram is slightly wider and sharper and was clearly added later. There is an additional marker for Gracie of the tablet type (rectangular slab), lying next to the veteran's headstone for Hiram. The plot is bordered by a low concrete curb with raised posts at the corners and entrance (on the west side)
